When working on custom web application development, you need to publish an Angular application with SSR. In this case, you normally start thinking about a VPS, Docker, serverless functions, or some paid hosting platform.
But for a small website, MVP, pet project, demo, or development environment, a separate server can be too much.
You can deploy an Angular SSR application to Cloudflare Workers:

• without a VPS;

• without Nginx;

• without a running Node.js process;

• without Express;

• without paying anything at the beginning.
In this article, we will take an existing Angular SSR project, prepare it for Cloudflare Workers, and publish it online.
At the end, we will have:

• Angular server-side rendering;

• JavaScript, CSS, images, and other static files served by Cloudflare;

• a public URL like project-name.username.workers.dev;

• free hosting within the limits of the Cloudflare Workers Free plan.
Free does not mean unlimited. Cloudflare Workers has usage limits on the free plan. For a development environment, demo project, portfolio, or small website, these limits are usually enough. For serious custom web application development with high traffic, complex backend logic, or strict performance requirements, you should check the limits more carefully before using the free plan in production.
What We Are Going to Deploy
Let’s say we already have an Angular project with SSR enabled.
The project structure may look like this:
src/
├── app/
├── main.ts
├── main.server.ts
└── server.tsangular.json
package.json
tsconfig.jsonIn case SSR is not enabled yet, you can add it with:
ng add @angular/ssrAfter building the project, Angular normally creates two main folders:
dist/project-name/
├── browser/
└── server/The browser folder contains:

• JavaScript bundles;

• CSS files;

• images;

• fonts;

• other static files.
The server folder contains the code used to render Angular pages on the server.
On a normal Node.js server, this code usually runs through Express.
Cloudflare Workers uses a different model.
Why the Default Express Server Does Not Work Here
A standard Angular SSR project may have a server entry file that uses Express:
import express from 'express';const app = express();app.use(
express.static(browserDistFolder, {
maxAge: '1y',
index: false,
}),
);app.get('*', requestHandler);app.listen(4000);This is fine when you run Angular SSR on a normal Node.js server.
But Cloudflare Worker does not start a permanent HTTP server.
There is no reason to call:
app.listen(4000);Cloudflare receives the HTTP request itself and passes it to the exported fetch function.
A very basic Worker looks like this:
export default {
async fetch(request: Request): Promise<Response> {
return new Response('Hello from Cloudflare');
},
};So we need to replace this model:
Express + app.listen()with this one:
Cloudflare Worker + fetch()Angular SSR is still used. We only change the runtime around it.
Step 1. Install Wrangler
Wrangler is the official command-line tool for Cloudflare Workers.
Install it as a development dependency:
npm install --save-dev wranglerCheck that it works:
npx wrangler --versionThen log in to your Cloudflare account:
npx wrangler loginThe command will open a browser window and ask you to allow access to your Cloudflare account.
You do not need to add a credit card to use the free plan.
Step 2. Check the Angular Server Configuration
Open angular.json and find the configuration of your Angular project.
The important part should look similar to this:
{
"server": "src/main.server.ts",
"outputMode": "server",
"ssr": {
"entry": "src/server.ts",
"platform": "neutral"
}
}The most important option here is:
"platform": "neutral"This tells Angular that the server bundle should not depend too much on the standard Node.js environment.
This matters because Cloudflare Workers uses its own runtime.
It supports standard web APIs such as:
Request
Response
fetch
URL
HeadersBut it is not a normal Node.js server.
Step 3. Replace Express with a Cloudflare Worker
Now we need to update src/server.ts.
The exact code can be different depending on your Angular version, but the general structure looks like this:
interface Env {
ASSETS: Fetcher;
}export const reqHandler = async (
request: Request,
env: Env,
context: ExecutionContext,
): Promise<Response> => {
const url = new URL(request.url); if (isStaticAsset(url.pathname)) {
return env.ASSETS.fetch(request);
} return renderAngularApplication(request);
};export default {
fetch: reqHandler,
};We have two types of requests here.
Static file requests
For example:
/main-ABC123.js
/styles-DEF456.css
/favicon.ico
/assets/logo.svgThese requests are handled by:
env.ASSETS.fetch(request)Cloudflare finds the file inside the Angular browser folder and returns it to the browser.
Angular page requests
For example:
/
/about
/products
/products/42These requests should be passed to Angular SSR.
Angular renders the page as HTML on the server. After that, the browser loads the client-side JavaScript and Angular continues working normally.
The request flow looks like this:
HTTP request
↓
Cloudflare Worker
↓
Check the URL
├── JS, CSS, images, fonts → Cloudflare Assets
│
└── Angular route → Angular SSR → HTMLThe Worker now takes the place of the Express server.
Step 4. Detect Static Files
A simple way to detect static files is to check whether the URL has a file extension:
function isStaticAsset(pathname: string): boolean {
return /\.[a-zA-Z0-9]+$/.test(pathname);
}Requests like these will be sent to ASSETS:
/styles.css
/main.js
/logo.svg
/font.woff2The basic Worker structure will look like this:
interface Env {
ASSETS: Fetcher;
}function isStaticAsset(pathname: string): boolean {
return /\.[a-zA-Z0-9]+$/.test(pathname);
}export const reqHandler = async (
request: Request,
env: Env,
context: ExecutionContext,
): Promise<Response> => {
const url = new URL(request.url); if (isStaticAsset(url.pathname)) {
return env.ASSETS.fetch(request);
} return renderAngularApplication(request);
};export default {
fetch: reqHandler,
};In this example, renderAngularApplication() means the SSR handler of your Angular application.
Its real implementation depends on your Angular version and on what you have inside main.server.ts.
The important part is that the final server entry exports a Cloudflare-compatible fetch handler.
It should not start Express with app.listen().
Step 5. Add Cache Headers for Static Files
Angular adds hashes to production file names:
main-NAGXKJ4P.js
styles-72DPLK3A.css
chunk-U4D9DBWQ.jsWhen the content changes, the file name also changes.
Because of this, these files can be cached for a long time.
We can add this header:
Cache-Control: public, max-age=31536000, immutableHere is a helper for static assets:
async function serveStaticAsset(
request: Request,
env: Env,
): Promise<Response> {
const response = await env.ASSETS.fetch(request); if (!response.ok) {
return response;
} const headers = new Headers(response.headers); headers.set(
'Cache-Control',
'public, max-age=31536000, immutable',
); return new Response(response.body, {
status: response.status,
statusText: response.statusText,
headers,
});
}Now we can use it inside the Worker:
export const reqHandler = async (
request: Request,
env: Env,
context: ExecutionContext,
): Promise<Response> => {
const url = new URL(request.url); if (isStaticAsset(url.pathname)) {
return serveStaticAsset(request, env);
} return renderAngularApplication(request);
};This replaces the cache configuration we normally use with Express:
express.static(browserDistFolder, {
maxAge: '1y',
immutable: true,
});But now we do not need Express at all.
Step 6. Create the Wrangler Configuration
Create this file in the project root:
wrangler.jsoncAdd the following configuration:
{
"$schema": "node_modules/wrangler/config-schema.json", "name": "angular-ssr-demo", "main": "./dist/angular-ssr-demo/server/server.mjs", "compatibility_date": "2026-07-01", "compatibility_flags": [
"nodejs_compat"
], "assets": {
"binding": "ASSETS",
"directory": "./dist/angular-ssr-demo/browser"
}
}Let’s look at the main options.
name
"name": "angular-ssr-demo"This is the name of the Worker.
It will be used in the default Cloudflare URL:
angular-ssr-demo.username.workers.devThe name should be unique inside your Cloudflare account.
main
"main": "./dist/angular-ssr-demo/server/server.mjs"This is the compiled Angular server entry file.
Cloudflare runs this file when it needs to render a page with SSR.
Do not point main to the browser folder.
In that case, Cloudflare may publish only a static SPA, and SSR will not run.
compatibility_date
"compatibility_date": "2026-07-01"This option defines the runtime behavior and available Cloudflare Worker features.
For a new project, you can use a recent date and keep it fixed in the repository.
nodejs_compat
"compatibility_flags": [
"nodejs_compat"
]This flag adds support for some Node.js APIs.
But it does not turn Cloudflare Worker into a full Node.js server.
You still should not start Express or call app.listen().
assets
"assets": {
"binding": "ASSETS",
"directory": "./dist/angular-ssr-demo/browser"
}This tells Cloudflare where the Angular static files are located.
The binding name:
ASSETSmatches the TypeScript environment interface:
interface Env {
ASSETS: Fetcher;
}Step 7. Add Preview and Deploy Commands
Open package.json and add these scripts:
{
"scripts": {
"build": "ng build",
"preview": "npm run build && wrangler dev",
"deploy": "npm run build && wrangler deploy"
}
}Now you can test the project locally:
npm run previewWrangler will build the project and start a local Cloudflare Workers environment.
You should see a local URL similar to:
http://localhost:8787Open it in your browser and check:

• the home page opens;

• direct links to nested routes work;

• CSS and JavaScript files load;

• there are no errors in the browser console;

• the server returns rendered HTML.
How to Check That SSR Really Works
Opening the website in a browser is not enough.
A normal Angular SPA can also look completely fine after JavaScript loads.
You can check the HTML with curl:
curl http://localhost:8787/productsThe response should already contain the page content:
<app-root>
<app-products>
...
</app-products>
</app-root>When app-root is empty and the content appears only after JavaScript starts, SSR is probably not working.
You can also open the page source:
view-source:http://localhost:8787/productsThe page content should be present directly in the returned HTML.
Step 8. Deploy the Application
When the local test works, run:
npm run deployWrangler will:

• build the Angular application;

• upload the server bundle;

• upload the static files;

• create or update the Worker;

• return the public URL.
The output may look similar to this:
Uploaded angular-ssr-demo
Deployed angular-ssr-demo
https://angular-ssr-demo.username.workers.devYour Angular SSR application is now online.
Common Problem: Only the browser Folder Was Published
This problem can be a little confusing.
The deployment completes successfully. The website opens. Angular routing works.
But SSR is not working.
In the logs, you may see something like:
Read 29 files from the assets directory:
dist/angular-ssr-demo/browserAt the same time, this file is never executed:
dist/angular-ssr-demo/server/server.mjsThis usually means that Cloudflare was configured only to publish static files.
The correct configuration should contain both paths:
{
"main": "./dist/angular-ssr-demo/server/server.mjs",
"assets": {
"binding": "ASSETS",
"directory": "./dist/angular-ssr-demo/browser"
}
}The main file runs Angular SSR.
The assets.directory folder contains CSS, JavaScript, images, and other static files.
How Much Does It Cost?
For a small project, it can cost nothing.
The free Cloudflare Workers plan has limits, but it is usually enough for:

• development environments;

• MVPs;

• pet projects;

• portfolios;

• landing pages;

• docu
